title: NFL 32: Notes on each NFL team entering Week 5
text:
Home / Sports NFL 32: Notes on each NFL team entering Week 5 
By Ryan O'Halloran & Hays Carlyon Thu, Oct 8, 2015 @ 10:04 pm | updated Thu, Oct 8, 2015 @ 10:09 pm Photos AP New England Patriots safety Devin McCourty (32) intercepts a pass thrown by Jacksonville Jaguars quarterback Blake Bortles (5) and intended for Jaguars tight end Marcedes Lewis (89) in the first half of an NFL football game, Sunday, Sept. 27, 2015, in Foxborough, Mass. 
AFC 
EAST 
BUFFALO : Remember us saying the Bills are an every-other-week team? That means they’ll beat the Titans. 
MIAMI : People scoffed when we compared Ndamukong Suh to Albert Haynesworth. Who’s scoffing now? 
NEW ENGLAND : Patriots lead NFL in yards, passing yards, points, first downs per game and third down conversion rate. 
NY JETS : RB Chris Ivory enters Gang Green’s bye week with 314 rushing yards, third-best in the league. 
NORTH 
BALTIMORE : We know WR Steve Smith is retiring after season, but can he still do press conferences via Skype? 
CINCINNATI : Measuring stick game for Bengals, hosting Seattle, which flies cross-country on a short week. 
CLEVELAND : Browns one of only three teams (Saints, Redskins) to have five players with at least 10 catches. 
PITTSBURGH : It remains a mystery why Mike Tomlin uses Antonio Brown on punt returns. 
SOUTH 
HOUSTON : From the It Must Be A Misprint But It’s Not Dept. — Texans have been outscored 52-3 in second quarter. 
INDIANAPOLIS : Embarrassment of riches at receiver for Colts — Hilton, Dorsett and the emerging Moncrief. 
JAGUARS : We’ll see how much confidence Gus Bradley has in Jason Myers the first time offense reaches 35-yard line. 
TENNESSEE : Titans come out of bye to play three consecutive games at home — Buffalo, Miami and Atlanta. 
WEST 
DENVER : Its 18 sacks lead NFL and 11 players have at least one sack, led by 4.5 for DeMarcus Ware. 
KANSAS CITY : Offense gained 461 yards at Cincinnati last week … and kicked seven FGs. 
OAKLAND : Amari Cooper — the should-have-been Jaguars receiver — on pace for 96 catches and 1,356 yards. 
SAN DIEGO : Second-ranked passing game gets Antonio Gates back from suspension. 
Ryan O’Halloran , the Times-Union 
NFC 
EAST 
DALLAS : Cowboys defense gets boost with DE Greg Hardy (four-game suspension over) set to debut vs. Patriots. 
NY GIANTS : Defense tops NFL against the run, but last against the pass. 
PHILADELPHIA : Offense hopes it found life with 20-point second-half output in loss to Redskins. 
WASHINGTON : Jay Gruden off to solid start at 2-2, tied atop division with Dallas and the Giants. 
NORTH 
CHICAGO : Bears were 10 of 17 on third down in 22-20 win over Raiders, ending an eight-game losing streak. 
DETROIT : DE Ziggy Ansah off to sizzling start with four sacks, yet Lions only winless team in NFL. 
GREEN BAY : Packers defense (No. 8 in NFL) held 49ers RB Carlos Hyde (22 total yards) in check. 
MINNESOTA : Vikings get bye week after giving up seven sacks last week in loss at Denver. 
SOUTH 
ATLANTA : Undefeated Falcons owning time of possession (34:17-25:43). Tied for third in NFL in most rushing attempts. 
CAROLINA : Bye week comes at good time to get LB Luke Kuechly healthy from Week 1 concussion. 
NEW ORLEANS : Saints have allowed at least 20 points in every game and yielding most yards per play in NFL. 
TAMPA BAY : Bucs are falling behind early. They’ve been outscored 38-6 in first quarter this season. 
WEST 
ARIZONA : Cardinals won’t be the last defense Rams RB Todd Gurley (146 rushing yards) runs through. 
ST. LOUIS : Expect CB Janoris Jenkins to snap Aaron Rodgers’ pick-free streak at Lambeau Field. 
SAN FRANCISCO : Free-agent addition WR Torrey Smith has nine catches in four games. 
SEATTLE : Legion of Boom overshadows an excellent linebacker corps. 
Hays Carlyon , the Times-Union
